You could argue that
cities should first

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:31.840
make money and then
reculture themselves.

01:08:31.840 --> 01:08:35.810
The first [INAUDIBLE]
argued in the Third World

01:08:35.810 --> 01:08:40.580
economic environment
that first, make cities.

01:08:40.580 --> 01:08:45.680
For instance, an alternative
to [? Chandigarh ?]

01:08:45.680 --> 01:08:49.310
was presented as a
city of mud growing,

01:08:49.310 --> 01:08:52.670
eventually, into a city of gold.

01:08:52.670 --> 01:08:57.140
The images is that
the important thing

01:08:57.140 --> 01:09:02.370
is to establish the economic
system, make it work.

01:09:02.370 --> 01:09:07.460
And then invest in the
superficial aspects

01:09:07.460 --> 01:09:10.580
or the superior
aspects of culture.

01:09:10.580 --> 01:09:14.240
Here, in a city in
which there aren't

01:09:14.240 --> 01:09:17.960
proper streets, in which people
get killed in the street,

01:09:17.960 --> 01:09:23.779
get killed anywhere else, here
is the cultural contribution.

01:09:23.779 --> 01:09:31.685
This is what the new
middle class need to enjoy.

01:09:31.685 --> 01:09:32.185
Next.

01:09:39.270 --> 01:09:43.800
The part of the Colombian
exhibition which involved

01:09:43.800 --> 01:09:49.649
the Court of Honor, the
major buildings on the flank

01:09:49.649 --> 01:09:55.800
and the electricity building,
the [INAUDIBLE] building

01:09:55.800 --> 01:09:59.850
[INAUDIBLE] administration,
entry by train,

01:09:59.850 --> 01:10:05.190
the base and statue of
the Republic, the harbour,

01:10:05.190 --> 01:10:06.000
and so on.

01:10:08.765 --> 01:10:09.265
Next.

01:10:14.740 --> 01:10:23.120
The Woman's Building, you
can see the Midway Plaisance

01:10:23.120 --> 01:10:29.900
in the distance with
the Ferris wheel

01:10:29.900 --> 01:10:36.620
in position, as opposed to
the neoclassical facades

01:10:36.620 --> 01:10:43.170
of the old part
of the exhibition.

01:10:43.170 --> 01:10:43.670
Next.

01:10:49.600 --> 01:10:56.080
Extraordinary historical
devices-- the crescent,

01:10:56.080 --> 01:11:01.535
the arch, the
isolated sculpture.

01:11:01.535 --> 01:11:02.035
Next.

01:11:06.780 --> 01:11:15.880
Louis Sullivan and Adler's
Transportation building whilst

01:11:15.880 --> 01:11:21.130
Sullivan rejected
the neoclassicism

01:11:21.130 --> 01:11:23.050
of this exhibition.

01:11:23.050 --> 01:11:27.640
He nevertheless had
enough attraction to it

01:11:27.640 --> 01:11:28.660
to build this building.

01:11:31.990 --> 01:11:35.500
The Administration
building, with a dam

01:11:35.500 --> 01:11:39.380
which is larger than the
Capitol in Washington.

01:11:39.380 --> 01:11:39.880
Next.

01:11:42.830 --> 01:11:44.220
Sorry, I made a mistake.

01:11:44.220 --> 01:11:47.300
This is a Woman's
Building by Sophia Hayden.

01:11:47.300 --> 01:11:50.000
In the interior of
the Woman's Building,

01:11:50.000 --> 01:11:53.360
a mixture of new
electrical equipment

01:11:53.360 --> 01:11:58.730
for the modern kitchen
and half-nude women

01:11:58.730 --> 01:12:03.680
dressed up in drapery as the
other half of the woman's life.

01:12:06.550 --> 01:12:07.050
Next.

01:12:11.290 --> 01:12:14.020
Ferris wheel.

01:12:14.020 --> 01:12:25.160
And you can see the Austrian
village, the Algerian,

01:12:25.160 --> 01:12:34.330
the Moorish Palace, the street
of Cairo, the German village,

01:12:34.330 --> 01:12:36.915
the Javanese village.

01:12:36.915 --> 01:12:37.415
Next.

01:12:41.420 --> 01:12:47.950
That's Sol Bloom, a
little older than 25.

01:12:47.950 --> 01:12:49.570
Next.

01:12:49.570 --> 01:12:53.350
There's a kind of
hybridity in looking

01:12:53.350 --> 01:12:56.500
at the history of cities.

01:12:56.500 --> 01:13:00.820
You could argue that
almost any city in motion

01:13:00.820 --> 01:13:05.980
will produce hybrid
versions of situations.

01:13:05.980 --> 01:13:11.320
We've had a hybrid version
of the independent woman--

01:13:11.320 --> 01:13:16.720
on the one hand, dressed up as
a nude model; on the other hand,

01:13:16.720 --> 01:13:19.655
percolating over a new
toaster in the kitchen.

01:13:22.800 --> 01:13:26.760
The same with the
American psyche--

01:13:26.760 --> 01:13:30.030
what do you go and see, the
largest manufacturing building

01:13:30.030 --> 01:13:31.140
in the world?

01:13:31.140 --> 01:13:33.630
Or come and enjoy
yourself seeing

01:13:33.630 --> 01:13:38.310
the exotics of Cairo street?

01:13:38.310 --> 01:13:38.810
Next.

01:13:41.990 --> 01:13:48.710
It all ends very quickly with
fires, one in the cold storage

01:13:48.710 --> 01:13:52.640
environment, another in the
Manufacturer's building.

01:13:52.640 --> 01:13:56.150
And this whole place is ruined.

01:13:56.150 --> 01:13:59.570
And it's back to scratch.

01:13:59.570 --> 01:14:00.070
Next.

01:14:04.470 --> 01:14:07.110
Pullman, Illinois,
the Florence Hotel

01:14:07.110 --> 01:14:10.620
on the right with
the clock tower,

01:14:10.620 --> 01:14:17.305
the typical plan of an
industrial manufacturing town.

01:14:17.305 --> 01:14:17.805
Next.

01:14:21.350 --> 01:14:24.890
The Arcade, perhaps one
of the earliest shopping

01:14:24.890 --> 01:14:27.860
centers in the United States.

01:14:27.860 --> 01:14:29.990
Next.

01:14:29.990 --> 01:14:34.520
1894, the workers and
the National militia

01:14:34.520 --> 01:14:37.725
are called out to
protect Pullman.

01:14:37.725 --> 01:14:38.225
Next.

01:14:41.270 --> 01:14:47.030
Burnham, on the extreme left,
at the City Business Club

01:14:47.030 --> 01:14:57.522
and his plan to create a girdle
around the city, six miles out,

01:14:57.522 --> 01:15:00.560
and to diagonalize
the grid where

01:15:00.560 --> 01:15:06.050
possible with diagonal systems,
leading to a newly created

01:15:06.050 --> 01:15:14.540
center civic promenade and
a large cultural enterprise

01:15:14.540 --> 01:15:17.685
along the waterfront
and the harbor.

01:15:17.685 --> 01:15:18.185
Next.

01:15:26.350 --> 01:15:34.000
Originally, all the railroads
would follow the same pattern,

01:15:34.000 --> 01:15:36.780
entering the center of the city.

01:15:36.780 --> 01:15:43.840
The park system would
be greenery located

01:15:43.840 --> 01:15:48.485
in [INAUDIBLE] system.

01:15:51.620 --> 01:15:52.120
Next.

01:16:04.580 --> 01:16:07.910
Burnham had large
drawings of Paris.

01:16:07.910 --> 01:16:16.020
Haussmann was a long
time in advance.

01:16:16.020 --> 01:16:21.210
But neoclassical Paris was what
Burnham was using as a model.

01:16:24.490 --> 01:16:24.990
Next.

01:16:30.270 --> 01:16:35.980
This is the German
urbanist, [INAUDIBLE]

01:16:35.980 --> 01:16:42.160
attempt to revise
the grid system

01:16:42.160 --> 01:16:48.070
by cutting it in to
different systems,

01:16:48.070 --> 01:16:50.650
breaking it up in
places, leaving it

01:16:50.650 --> 01:16:53.380
where it is in
places, instituting

01:16:53.380 --> 01:16:56.500
a different [INAUDIBLE]
in some places,

01:16:56.500 --> 01:17:00.160
and really revamping
the whole system.

01:17:00.160 --> 01:17:05.230
He was also attracted
by [INAUDIBLE]

01:17:05.230 --> 01:17:12.040
tall office building
and residential towers

01:17:12.040 --> 01:17:15.110
as a proposition.

01:17:15.110 --> 01:17:15.610
Next.

01:17:18.140 --> 01:17:23.340
And the last of this is
Mario Gandelsonas' book

01:17:23.340 --> 01:17:29.210
The Urban Text, an attempt to
take the grid and the river

01:17:29.210 --> 01:17:39.260
and to reframe it, is best I
can put it, as a set of steps

01:17:39.260 --> 01:17:44.300
that you take in reconstructing
the deep structure of this grid

01:17:44.300 --> 01:17:49.670
and river into systems
that look like that.

01:17:49.670 --> 01:17:57.770
Peter [? Eisenman ?] used the
system in studios at Harvard.

01:17:57.770 --> 01:18:01.010
If we have a chance at
one of the next classes,

01:18:01.010 --> 01:18:04.390
I will show some of that work.

01:18:07.040 --> 01:18:08.840
It's a set of--

01:18:08.840 --> 01:18:10.790
it's based on the
notion that you

01:18:10.790 --> 01:18:15.740
can dig deeply into
of an environment,

01:18:15.740 --> 01:18:19.640
reconstruct it, and
re-elementize it

01:18:19.640 --> 01:18:21.860
in a new way, which is that.

01:18:21.860 --> 01:18:24.020
I don't know what
the hell it means.

01:18:24.020 --> 01:18:26.840
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHS]

01:18:26.840 --> 01:18:30.230
JULIAN BEINART: It has
no practical value.

01:18:30.230 --> 01:18:32.450
You should look at the
book The Urban Text

01:18:32.450 --> 01:18:34.220
and decide on your own.

01:18:34.220 --> 01:18:35.360
I'll give you my opinion.

01:18:44.200 --> 01:18:47.260
Chicago is now considered as
one of the greenest cities

01:18:47.260 --> 01:18:48.135
in the United States.

01:18:54.460 --> 01:18:56.784
What does that mean?

01:18:56.784 --> 01:18:59.024
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

01:18:59.024 --> 01:19:00.535
JULIAN BEINART: Sorry?

01:19:00.535 --> 01:19:04.235
STUDENT: The green spaces
are mostly private.

01:19:04.235 --> 01:19:06.110
JULIAN BEINART: Does it
matter what they are?

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:14.530
Certainly not as far as
the environment, the air,

01:19:14.530 --> 01:19:17.220
and pollution is concerned.

01:19:17.220 --> 01:19:20.850
If you privatized all
the roofs of buildings

01:19:20.850 --> 01:19:24.450
and made them green, you'd
have an enormous effect

01:19:24.450 --> 01:19:28.650
on the energy output in a city.

01:19:37.270 --> 01:19:40.160
I'll just leave--
if you want to,

01:19:40.160 --> 01:19:43.840
I'll give you the reference
to the study which

01:19:43.840 --> 01:19:47.345
posits Chicago is the greatest
city in the United States.

01:19:50.170 --> 01:19:53.466
It's largely the greening
of the roofs of buildings.

01:20:00.140 --> 01:20:01.475
Chicago can do anything.

01:20:04.600 --> 01:20:08.620
It's an example of a
city as an artifact which

01:20:08.620 --> 01:20:13.270
manufactures-- re-manufactures
itself almost at will,

01:20:13.270 --> 01:20:16.165
just through a kind
of sense and will.

01:20:19.084 --> 01:20:21.780
I mean, that sense of will--

01:20:21.780 --> 01:20:24.570
STUDENT: How much
of that will gets

01:20:24.570 --> 01:20:27.930
lost once the city
becomes institutionalized?

01:20:27.930 --> 01:20:30.150
JULIAN BEINART: A lot.

01:20:30.150 --> 01:20:34.080
You just can't bribe
your way through.

01:20:34.080 --> 01:20:36.990
No, absolutely.

01:20:36.990 --> 01:20:41.460
Chicago as a story is
a story of free will.

01:20:41.460 --> 01:20:45.990
Anybody coming in from anywhere
making it, and behaving

01:20:45.990 --> 01:20:48.073
like an important person.

01:20:48.073 --> 01:20:50.240
STUDENT: There's a sense
of rapaciousness in the DNA

01:20:50.240 --> 01:20:50.907
that you showed.

01:20:50.907 --> 01:20:55.020
JULIAN BEINART: Absolutely,
absolutely, absolutely.

01:20:59.830 --> 01:21:04.060
The social cost of the
free-sector environment was

01:21:04.060 --> 01:21:07.090
slowly picked up
as the country--

01:21:07.090 --> 01:21:08.275
I mean, this was a pretty--

01:21:13.490 --> 01:21:20.840
[INAUDIBLE] I was
trying to think

01:21:20.840 --> 01:21:23.240
of the percentage
of Black people

01:21:23.240 --> 01:21:27.240
in this country who still
live below the poverty line.

01:21:27.240 --> 01:21:32.210
I think [? 16%, ?] or 50%
of the Black population

01:21:32.210 --> 01:21:38.780
lived below the
poverty line in 2013.

01:21:38.780 --> 01:21:43.160
This is from William Julius
Jones' work at Harvard.

01:21:43.160 --> 01:21:45.680
And the statistics
are borne out.

01:21:45.680 --> 01:21:49.700
This country has never
caught up with the capacity

01:21:49.700 --> 01:21:53.510
to socialize poverty.

01:21:53.510 --> 01:21:56.570
It's assumed that--

01:21:56.570 --> 01:21:59.960
Mitt Romney is an arch
example of somebody

01:21:59.960 --> 01:22:05.210
who believes that the free
market system will eventually

01:22:05.210 --> 01:22:10.400
produce enough social
benefit to take

01:22:10.400 --> 01:22:12.610
care of the exaggerations
of the market.

01:22:19.280 --> 01:22:20.780
I don't know what else to say.

01:22:20.780 --> 01:22:22.400
It's such a big generalization.

01:22:22.400 --> 01:22:26.990
We'll come into it
later in this class.

01:22:26.990 --> 01:22:33.470
Certainly, the European cities,
from Engels onwards, face the--

01:22:33.470 --> 01:22:35.570
and the Communist
Party never had

01:22:35.570 --> 01:22:39.830
any leverage in this country.

01:22:39.830 --> 01:22:42.380
The trade union
movement in this country

01:22:42.380 --> 01:22:44.630
doesn't resemble the
British trade union

01:22:44.630 --> 01:22:47.795
movement in any way at all.

01:22:47.795 --> 01:22:52.670
The British trade union movement
educates people in voting,

01:22:52.670 --> 01:22:54.755
for instance.

01:22:54.755 --> 01:22:57.560
The American trade
union movement is--

01:23:00.160 --> 01:23:03.400
half of the American South
doesn't involve the trade union

01:23:03.400 --> 01:23:05.140
anyway.

01:23:05.140 --> 01:23:09.550
And that's where most of the new
automobile manufacturing plants

01:23:09.550 --> 01:23:11.190
are going.